(1) The agency shall not, through other means, including rulemaking,
increase or charge any additional fees, impose any other expense, restriction,
requirements, or cost to a commercial paddle craft operator related to an
operator's parking lot pass or annual permit.
(2) The agency shall manage boat ramps and parking lots for public
safety, but shall not impose restrictions on the hours of operation for boat ramps
and parking lots to the extent that such restrictions are shorter in duration than
existing boat ramp or parking lot hours of operation.
(3) The restrictions imposed on the agency under subdivisions (b)(1) and
(2) are effective through June 30, 2027.
(c)
(1) Subject to subdivision (c)(2), a commercial paddle craft operator who
fails to obtain a permit or remit payment for the use of an agency boat ramp
under this section is:
(A) Subject to a fine of one thousand dollars ($1,000); and
(B) Prohibited from applying for a permit for a period of time to be
determined by the agency.
(2) Prior to the imposition of the penalty prescribed under subdivision
(c)(1), a commercial paddle craft operator has sixty (60) days from the date the
fine was imposed to submit sufficient proof to the agency that the violation has
been corrected and, upon a determination of such correction by the agency, the
fine must be waived and the operator may apply for a permit.
69-9-230.
Beginning October 1, 2025, retailers shall report annually to the department of
revenue the sales of non-motorized vessels and equipment used in association with
paddle sports, including the following items:
(1) Kayaks;
